</div>

<p>GHK-Cu is a <a href="/articles/ghk-cu-copper-peptide-guide">naturally occurring copper peptide</a> that plays vital roles in tissue repair and regeneration. Research shows it becomes less abundant as we age, contributing to visible signs of aging in skin and hair.</p>

<p>This decline accelerates after age 40. By age 60, our GHK-Cu levels drop to just 40% of what they were in our 20s. This guide examines the science behind this remarkable compound.</p>

<p>We will explore how it works at a cellular level and how you can use it safely. Always consult your dermatologist before starting new skin treatments.</p>

<hr class="sep"/>

<h2>Understanding GHK-Cu: The Basics</h2>

<p>GHK-Cu is a small peptide composed of three amino acids (glycine-histidine-lysine) bound to copper. It is naturally present in human plasma, saliva, and urine.</p>

<p>The peptide was first identified by scientists studying <a href="/articles/bpc-157-complete-guide">wound healing processes</a> in the 1970s. They noticed it accelerated healing in burn patients and tissue regeneration.</p>

<p>Our bodies produce less GHK-Cu as we get older. This decline correlates with reduced tissue repair capacity. By age 60, GHK-Cu levels are about 60% lower than in young adulthood.</p>

<p>This reduction contributes to slower wound healing and less resilient skin. It is one reason why skin repairs slower as we age.</p>

<div class="d d-t">
  <div class="s">Dermatology Insight</div>
  <p>GHK-Cu is one of the few ingredients that actually communicates with skin cells. It tells them to behave like younger cells. It is not just a surface treatment but a cellular communicator.</p>
</div>

<h3>How GHK-Cu Functions in the Body</h3>

<p>GHK-Cu works through multiple biological pathways. It activates genes that promote tissue regeneration and repair.</p>

<div class="g2">
  <div class="cd cb">
    <div class="tg">Signaling</div>
    <h3>Cellular Communication</h3>
    <p>Activates genes involved in tissue repair. Stimulates fibroblasts to produce more collagen types I and III.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="cd ct">
    <div class="tg">Protection</div>
    <h3>Antioxidant Defense</h3>
    <p>Increases production of antioxidant enzymes like superoxide dismutase. Helps modulate inflammatory responses.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="g2">
  <div class="cd cp">
    <div class="tg">Regeneration</div>
    <h3>Stem Cell Activation</h3>
    <p>Encourages stem cells to repair damaged tissue. Promotes new blood vessel formation in healing areas.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="cd ca">
    <div class="tg">Remodeling</div>
    <h3>ECM Restructuring</h3>
