<p>Start at the lower end and increase gradually. Higher concentrations do not always mean faster results, and can sometimes cause unnecessary irritation.</p>

<hr class="sep"/>

<h2>Safety and Precautions</h2>

<p>GHK-Cu is generally well-tolerated, but some precautions apply. Always consult a healthcare provider before starting any new treatment.</p>

<p>This is especially important if you have sensitive skin or existing conditions. Your dermatologist can recommend the best approach for your skin type.</p>

<h3>Potential Side Effects</h3>

<p>Most side effects are mild and temporary:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Mild tingling during initial use (usually subsides in 1-2 weeks)</li>
  <li>Temporary redness at application site</li>
  <li>Blue-green tint with some formulations (washes off)</li>
  <li>Rare allergic reactions (discontinue if occurs)</li>
</ul>

<p>Serious side effects are extremely rare. Stop use if you experience persistent irritation or rash.</p>

<h3>Who Should Avoid GHK-Cu</h3>

<div class="cd cr">
  <div class="tg">Caution</div>
  <h3>Contraindications</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Copper allergies</strong>: Those with known copper sensitivity</li>
    <li><strong>Wilson's disease</strong>: A copper metabolism disorder</li>
    <li><strong>Pregnant/nursing women</strong>: Limited safety data available</li>
    <li><strong>Children</strong>: Not recommended under age 18</li>
  </ul>
  <p>If you have any medical conditions, consult your doctor before use. They can assess potential interactions with medications.</p>
</div>

<div class="d d-r">
  <div class="s">Important Safety Note</div>
  <p>While serious side effects are rare, everyone's skin is different. We always recommend patch testing new products behind the ear for 48 hours before full-face application. If persistent irritation occurs, discontinue use and consult a dermatologist. They can recommend alternative treatments if needed.</p>
</div>

